column8:
Broken auto glass can go in the garbage:
•Glass must fit in your bin with the lid closed.
•Don’t exceed the weight limits printed on your bin.
column10: Bring auto glass to city transfer stations. Fees apply.

column8: Bike parts smaller than 3-inches go in the garbage.
column10:
Donate or resell usable bikes and parts to scrap metal dealers or community-oriented bike shops like Bike Works or Recycled Cycles.

Bring bikes and parts to city transfer stations to be recycled. No fee.
column16:
Clean metal bike parts 3-inches or larger can go in the recycling:

Items must fit in your bin with the lid closed.
Don’t exceed the weight limits printed on your bin.

column12:
Bring brake and transmission fluids to a household hazardous waste facility:
•Put brake and transmission fluids in a sealed container that is 5-gallons or less.
•Limit 50-gallons per trip.

For more information, call our household hazards line at (206) 296-4692. Hours are 9 a.m. – 4:30 p.m., Monday through Friday.
column17: Don’t pour brake and transmission fluids down drains or toilets, down storm drains, or into soil. These all cause water pollution.

column10: Styro Recycle in Kent accepts Styrofoam blocks, packing sheets, and packing peanuts for recycling.
column17: Don’t reuse broken car seats or car seats that have been in accidents. It isn’t safe.

column5:
Donate car seats in good condition to local thrift stores.

Resell or give it away using sites like Craigslist, Freecycle, and Buy Nothing.
column8: Old and expired child car seats go in the garbage.
Car parts 3-inches or smaller on any side can go in the garbage.
column10: Many scrap metal dealers will buy car parts.
column17: Car parts aren’t accepted for recycling because they contain grease, which contaminates other recyclable items.

column10: Bring flares that don’t contain an explosive charge to a household hazardous waste facility. No fee.
column23: For flares with an explosive charge, call the Seattle Police Firing Range at (206) 684-7470.

column8: Empty gas cans that are 5-gallons or smaller can go in the garbage. Leave lid off empty can for 2 days before putting in garbage to release gas fumes.

column12:
Bring gasoline to a household hazardous waste facility:
•Put gas in a sealed container that is 5-gallons or less.
•Use gasoline-compatible containers (not food or milk jugs).
•Limit 30-gallons per trip.

column7: You must drain all gas and oil from lawn mowers and other power equipment. Bring emptied mowers and equipment to city transfer stations. No charge for lawn mowers.
column12:
Bring gas and oil to a household hazardous waste facility. No fee.
•Don’t mix fluids together!
•Put fluids in a sealed container that is 5 gallons or less.
•Limit 50 gallons per trip.
column13: Donate lawn mowers or power equipment in working condition to local thrift stores. Call first to confirm acceptance policies.

column10:
Bring license plates to a vehicle licensing office or mail them to:

Department of Licensing
 1125 Washington St. SE
 Olympia, WA 98504
column16: Remove the tabs and bend the license plates before putting in the recycling.

column7: Bring up to 5 gallons of oil per a trip to city transfer stations. No fee.
column12: Bring contaminated oil that contains solvents, bleach, or other materials to a household hazardous waste facility. No fee.
column17:
Motor oil can be recycled if it doesn’t contain solvents, bleach, or other materials.

Never pour motor oil on the ground or down the drain; it can pollute our waterways and the environment.
column25:
You can recycle up to 2 gallons of motor oil on each recycling collection day:
1.Pour cooled oil into a 1-gallon plastic container with a tight-fitting, screw-on lid.
2.Label the container with your name and address.
3.Set up to 2 labeled 1-gallon containers on the curb next to your recycling bin.
4.Apartment / Condo residents: Set out up to 2 labeled 1-gallon containers per cart at your building/complex.

column8: Empty motor oil containers go in the garbage. They can’t be recycled.
column10:
Bring partially full motor oil containers to:
•City transfer stations. Fees apply.
•A household hazardous waste facility. No fee.

column8: Puncture the oil filter and drain the oil into a container for 24 hours. Seal drained filter in a plastic bag and put in the garbage.
column10: Bring drained or full oil filters to a household hazardous waste facility. No fee.

column12:
Bring automotive fluids (such as brake, transmission, hydraulic, or power steering fluids) to a household hazardous waste facility:
•Put fluids in a sealed container that is 5-gallons or less.
•Limit 50-gallons per trip.
column15: Don’t mix fluids with used motor oil!

column10: Bring up to 4 tires per visit to city transfer stations. Fees apply.
Many charitable organizations accept vehicles and provide a receipt for a tax deduction.

From December 26 to January 31, bring Christmas trees to city transfer stations for free. Starting February 1, regular fees apply.
•Trees should not exceed 8-feet in length and must be free of decoration.
•Trunks should not exceed 4-inches in diameter.
•The stations will accept up to 3 trees per vehicle.
column24:
From December 26 to January 31, holiday trees, wreaths, and greens can be composted for free. Place on the curb next to your food and yard waste cart on your regular collection day.
•Flocked and plastic trees or wreaths will be charged as extra garbage.
•Remove all decorations and lights, tinsel, metal clips, ornaments and bows.
•Trees must be cut into lengths to 4-feet or shorter.
•For bundling branches, use sisal string or twine (not plastic).

At apartments – Two trees may be placed next to each food and yard waste cart at no extra charge each collection day. Each additional tree will be picked up as extra yard waste (fees apply).

column7:
Bring untreated wood waste to city transfer stations. Charge is $13 per load (limit 4 per load).

All pieces must be 4 feet or less in length and 4 inches or less in diameter.
Nails and staples are okay.
column17: Compost processing equipment removes metal staples and nails. However, the equipment can’t remove plastic.
column18:
Clean, untreated and unpainted wood goes in the food and yard waste.

All pieces must be 4 inches or less in diameter and 4 feet or less in length.
Put sawdust or shavings in paper bags or boxes to keep from scattering.
Avoid extra charges – Items should fit in your bin with the lid closed.
Don’t exceed the weight limits printed on your bin.
column24:
Bundles can be set next to the bin. Charge is $145 per ton as part of a load

Tie bundles with natural twine. No plastic allowed.
Bundles must be 2 feet or less in diameter.

column8: Corks go in the garbage. They are too dense to compost or recycle.
column10: Corks can also be recycled through the Cork ReHarvest Program, which has drop boxes at PCC, Whole Foods Markets, and Wine World Warehouses.

column8: Fireplace and briquette ashes must be completely cooled, wetted, and placed in a closed box or bag. This prevents ash from scattering when your garbage is collected.

column7: Bring lumber and wood boards to city transfer stations. Charge is $13 per load (limit 4 per load).
column8:
Painted or treated wood can go in the garbage:

Break wood down so it fits in your bin with the lid closed.
Make sure it doesn’t exceed the weight limits printed on your bin.

column7: Bring pallets to city transfer stations. Charge is $13 per load (limit 4 per load).
column8:
Pallets made from treated wood can be broken down and put in the garbage:
•Items must fit in your bin with the lid closed.
•Don’t exceed the weight limits printed on your bin.
column18:
Break pallets made from untreated wood into pieces that are:
•4 inches or less in diameter
•4 feet or less in length
•Remove any nails or metallic items.
column24: Items that do not fit in your bin with the lid closed may be put in a plastic bag and set next to your garbage bin on collection day. Each bulky item is a charge of $30.

column8:
Painted or treated wood can go in the garbage:
•All pieces must be less than 4-inches in diameter and under 4-feet long.
•Avoid extra charges – Break lumber and boards down so they fit in your bin with the lid closed.
column10: Donate or resell reusable lumber through building supply businesses that specialize in salvage or reusable materials.
column18:
Unpainted and untreated wood can go in the food and yard waste:
•Pieces should be less than 4-inches in diameter and under 4-feet long to avoid extra fees.
•Remove nails and all other non-wood materials.
•Avoid extra charges – Break lumber and boards down so they fit in your bin with the lid closed.

column8: Painted or treated wood shavings, scraps, and sawdust go in the garbage. Put sawdust and shavings in a bag and tie off.
column18: Clean, untreated wood shavings, scraps, and sawdust go in the food and yard waste. Put sawdust or shavings in a closed paper bag or box to contain it.

column10:
From December 26 to January 31, bring Christmas trees to city transfer stations for free. Starting February 1, regular fees apply.
•Trees should not exceed 8-feet in length and must be free of decoration.
•Trunks should not exceed 4-inches in diameter.
•The stations will accept up to 3 trees per vehicle
column24:
From December 26 to January 31, holiday trees, wreaths, and greens can be composted for free. Place on the curb next to your food and yard waste cart on your regular collection day.
•Flocked and plastic trees or wreaths will be charged as extra garbage.
•Remove all decorations and lights, tinsel, metal clips, ornaments and bows.
•Trees must be cut into lengths to 4-feet or shorter.
•For bundling branches, use sisal string or twine (not plastic).

At apartments – Two trees may be placed next to each food and yard waste cart at no extra charge each collection day. Each additional tree will be picked up as extra yard waste (fees apply).

column7: Bring dirt contaminated with non-hazardous materials like plastic, wood, or metal to city transfer stations. Charge is $30 per item (limit 2 per load) or $8 per item plus $145 per ton for other materials if part of a larger load.
column8: Dirt contaminated with non-hazardous materials like plastic, wood, or metal can go in the garbage if it doesn’t exceed the weight limits printed on your bin.
column23: For dirt that contains hazardous materials, call the household hazards line at (206) 296-4692. Hours are 9 a.m. – 4:30 p.m., Monday through Friday.

column7: Bring soil to city transfer stations. Soil is disposed of as garbage. Charge for garbage is a minimum of $30, for up to 420 lbs. or $145 per ton.
column8: Soil can go in your garbage if it doesn’t exceed the weight limits printed on your bin.

column10: Bring large amounts of grass clippings and sod to city transfer stations. Fees apply.
column18: Grass clippings and small amounts of sod can go in the food and yard waste. Don’t exceed the weight limits printed on your bin.
House plants go in the food and yard waste. Remove plants from potting soil and planters.

column10: Bring leaves or non-woody yard waste to city transfer stations. Fees apply.
column18:
Leaves and non-woody yard waste go in the food and yard waste.
•Items must fit in your bin with the lid closed.
•Don’t exceed the weight limits printed on your bin.

column8: Bag dog waste, cat waste, and used kitty litter. Tie off the bags and put in the garbage.
column17:
Never flush kitty litter down the toilet!

Pet waste can’t be composted in the food and yard waste or in backyard composting bins.
You can give your plant a new home through your neighborhood Buy Nothing group or PlantAmnesty.
column18: Plants and trees go in the food and yard waste. All pieces must be less than 4-inches in diameter and under 4-feet long.

column8: Dirty or ceramic plant pots go in the garbage.
column17: Ask about reuse and recycling options where you buy plant pots. Some garden stores and nurseries will take back plastic pots and reuse them.
column19: Empty and rinsed plastic plant pots go in the recycling.

column7: Bring rocks and gravel to city transfer stations. They are charged as garbage. Charge for garbage is $145 per ton, minimum charge of $30 covers up to 420 lbs.
column8: Rocks and gravel can go in your garbage if they don’t exceed the weight limits printed on your bin, and fit in your bin with the lid completely closed. No individual rock should be larger than 2 feet by 2 feet.
column13: Gravel in good condition may be accepted by local salvaged building material businesses.

column7:
Bring trees and brush to city transfer stations. Charge is $13 per load (limit 4 per load).
•All trees, brush, or branches must be 8 feet or less in length.
•All pieces must be 8 inches or less in diameter.
column18:
Trees, brush, and branches go in the food and yard waste:
•Cut down to 4 inches or less in diameter and 4 feet or less in length.
•Avoid extra charges – Items should fit in your bin with the lid closed.
•Don’t exceed the weight limits printed on your bin.
column24:
Bundle trees and brush and set next to the bin. Charge is $145 per ton as part of a load
•Tie bundles with natural twine. No plastic allowed.
•Bundles must be 2 feet or less in diameter.

column8: Painted or treated wood shavings, scraps, and sawdust go in the garbage. Put sawdust and shavings in a bag and tie off.
column18: Clean, untreated wood shavings, scraps, and sawdust go in the food and yard waste. Put sawdust or shavings in a closed paper bag or box to contain it.

column8: Noxious weeds should be bagged, tied off, and placed in the garbage. For more information about noxious weeds, visit Noxious Weeds in King County, Washington.
